From Halifax, a 45min drive took us to Shubenacadie - an interesting community with Miâ€™kmaq origins: "The Mi'kmaq spelling, Sipekne'katik, means the area where the wild turnips or wild potatoes grow.â€

With Miâ€™kmaq and Acadian history subtly around, Shubenacadie also boasts to be the â€œMilk Capital of Canadaâ€!Â  We had to stop in the <strong>Shubenacadie Tin Smith Shop Museum</strong> for a quick look around (and also purchase items from its super â€˜craftâ€™ gift shop).

<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-572" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/IMG_1367-e1473628194738-225x300.jpg" alt="img_1367" width="225" height="300" /> <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-573" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/IMG_1369-e1473628217841-225x300.jpg" alt="img_1369" width="225" height="300" />

