We followed the road along the Shubenacadie River, passing through dots of communities which were once, larger bustling areas.Â  A quick stop at the South Maitland Interpretive Centre which allowed for a spectacular view <em>over</em> the Bay of Fundy, by way of their boardwalk.Â  There was another trail leading along the marshes which is known to have superb â€˜birdingâ€™, perhaps another time.

Maitland is a small community and home to the oldest general store in Canada (circa 1839) and also the home of W. D. Lawrence, who built the largest wooden ship ever to be built in Canada!Â  The store is still running and the W.D. Lawrence Museum open â€“ this unassuming, sleepy little village, has a big story to tell and more than willing to share!Â  It also offers absolutely stunning, unparalleled views of the Bay of Fundy!

<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-584" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/IMG_0743-300x225.jpg" alt="img_0743" width="300" height="225" /> <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-585" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/IMG_0746-300x225.jpg" alt="img_0746" width="300" height="225" />

Although we didnâ€™t have time on this tour, this area also offers tidal bore rafting and mudsliding â€“ two unique options for those seeking adventure!

The quiet country road took us along the shoreline of the Bay of Fundy which offered spectacular scenery!Â  We popped into the <strong>East Hants Historical Society Museum</strong> (super little placeâ€¦ and for Titanic enthusiasts who think they have â€œseen it allâ€, think again! This museum houses an embalming table which is believed to have been used for John Jacob Astor â€“ the richest man aboard the Titanic!).

A short distance away is Anthony Provincial Park.Â  What a story this park had to tell us!Â  Itâ€™s beautiful, scenicâ€¦with a replica Atomic Bomb in it!

<em>â€œThe American Navy had been testing bombs in Florida and were using divers to retrieve them from the ocean. This was found to be cumbersome so the Navy searched North America for an alternative. The alternative was the Bay of Fundy. It was chosen because bombs could be dropped during high tide and then retrieved during low tide by driving onto the mud flats.Â â€œ</em>

There is so much more to this story, but WOW, in our back yard!

