Still working fishing villages, as can be evidenced by the fishing boats and lobster traps, the communities also boast a large artisan population.Â  This is not new.Â  Beginning in the 1900â€™s, this area attracted many artists, including Wallace MacKaskill, Joseph Purcell, William E. deGarthe and Jack L. Gray.Â  And who could blame them?Â  With gorgeous inlets surrounded by blue slate rocks, it truly is a beautiful, captivating area.

<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-509" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_1011-e1471083294981-225x300.jpg" alt="IMG_1011" width="225" height="300" /> <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-508" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_1007-225x300.jpg" alt="IMG_1007" width="225" height="300" />

<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-507" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_1004-e1471083253442-225x300.jpg" alt="IMG_1004" width="225" height="300" /> <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-506" src="http://bluediamondtours.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/IMG_1001-225x300.jpg" alt="IMG_1001" width="225" height="300" />

It is reported that Blue Rocks is â€œLunenburgâ€™s answer to Peggyâ€™s Coveâ€ and the fish shack, sitting in the water, is the most photographed building in the county!Â  Whatever may be, I think it is a perfect place for a picnic on the rocks.

